INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'LinkedIn Is Not a Job Board (And That Misconception Is Costing You)',
'<p>Let me say this directly: if you think LinkedIn is just where people go to find jobs, you are leaving real money on the table every single day. That belief is one of the most expensive myths in the entrepreneur world, and it is time we put it to rest. LinkedIn has over one billion members globally, and the majority of them are not job seekers. They are professionals, business owners, decision-makers, and executives who are actively using the platform to find solutions, build relationships, and do business.</p>
<p>Here is what makes LinkedIn different from every other social platform. When someone opens Instagram, they are looking at vacation photos and memes. When someone opens TikTok, they are there to be entertained. But when someone opens LinkedIn, they are in a business mindset. They are thinking about growth, problems they need to solve, vendors they need to find, and partnerships they want to build. That is the environment you want to be in as an entrepreneur.</p>
<p>The data backs this up. LinkedIn drives more than 80 percent of B2B leads generated through social media. Eighty percent. Facebook, Instagram, and Twitter combined make up the other 20. If you are an entrepreneur and you are spending all your time on Instagram and none of it on LinkedIn, you are fishing in the wrong pond. Your clients are not all on Instagram swiping through stories. Many of them are on LinkedIn reading articles, engaging with posts, and looking for exactly what you offer.</p>
<p>Now here is where it gets interesting for entrepreneurs specifically. LinkedIn is not just for service-based businesses or consultants. It works for product businesses, coaches, course creators, local businesses with national ambitions, and founders looking for investors or strategic partners. The platform is built around professional credibility, and as an entrepreneur, credibility is one of your most valuable assets. Every time you show up on LinkedIn with valuable content or a well-built profile, you are depositing into a trust account with your audience.</p>
<p>One of the biggest reasons entrepreneurs avoid LinkedIn is they feel like they do not belong there. They think, "I am not corporate enough" or "My business is too small." That thinking needs to go. LinkedIn was built for professionals, and if you run a business, you are a professional. Period. Some of the most engaging, fastest-growing voices on LinkedIn right now are small business owners and solopreneurs who showed up, shared their real experience, and built communities around their work.</p>
<p>The other hesitation I hear is about time. Entrepreneurs are busy. You are running operations, serving clients, managing finances, and trying to grow all at once. I get it. But here is the thing: LinkedIn rewards consistency over volume. You do not need to post five times a day or spend three hours on the platform. Twenty to thirty minutes a day, done with intention, can produce real results over time. This course is going to show you exactly how to use that time so none of it is wasted.</p>
<p>By the time you finish this module, you are going to see LinkedIn for what it actually is: a business development tool that works around the clock when you set it up right. Your profile stays up whether you are sleeping or on a client call. Your content keeps circulating after you post it. Connections you made six months ago can reach out today because they just saw your post and remembered you. That is leverage, and that is exactly what you need as an entrepreneur.</p>
<p>This is not about becoming an influencer or going viral. This is about building a presence that makes the right people take you seriously, reach out when they are ready, and refer you when someone asks. That is the LinkedIn strategy that actually moves the needle for entrepreneurs, and that is what this entire course is built around.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Log into LinkedIn and look at your profile as if you are a potential client seeing it for the first time. Write down three things that would make someone click away immediately.</li>
  <li>Search for two competitors or peers in your industry on LinkedIn. Look at their profiles and note what they are doing that you are not.</li>
  <li>Set a daily LinkedIn reminder on your phone for 20 minutes at a time that works with your schedule. Consistency starts with a system.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 1);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Who Is Actually on LinkedIn and Why That Matters for Your Business',
'<p>You cannot build a strategy without understanding the room you are walking into. So let us talk about who is actually on LinkedIn, because the answer might surprise you. The platform skews heavily toward decision-makers. Over 65 million LinkedIn users are in decision-making roles at their companies. That means when your content shows up in someone''s feed, there is a real chance that person can actually say yes to a purchase, a partnership, or a referral without having to ask anyone else.</p>
<p>The income demographics on LinkedIn are notable too. It consistently ranks as the social platform with the highest concentration of high-income users. That matters because when you are selling a service, a course, or a product, you want to be in front of people who have the budget to say yes. LinkedIn gives you that environment in a way that most other platforms do not.</p>
<p>Beyond income and title, LinkedIn is a place where professionals go when they are actively trying to solve problems. People search for vendors, service providers, and experts on LinkedIn regularly. They read articles. They look at who their connections are connected to. They engage with content from people they do not follow yet because the algorithm surfaces it to them. This is search behavior and discovery behavior happening at the same time, and you can benefit from both if your presence is set up correctly.</p>
<p>Now think about your specific business. Who is your ideal client or customer? If that person holds a professional title, works in a company of any size, runs their own business, or makes purchasing decisions, they are likely on LinkedIn. Even if you serve individuals rather than businesses, those individuals are on LinkedIn too. A financial coach whose clients are professionals in their 30s and 40s? They are on LinkedIn. A leadership consultant whose clients are mid-level managers hoping to become executives? Absolutely on LinkedIn. A product brand selling tools to business owners? Your buyers are right there.</p>
<p>The other group you need to think about on LinkedIn is referral sources. Even if your dream client does not seem like a LinkedIn user, the people who refer business to you probably are. Accountants, attorneys, financial advisors, business coaches, and consultants all use LinkedIn actively. Building relationships with those referral partners on LinkedIn can fill your pipeline in ways that feel almost passive once the relationships are in place.</p>
<p>Investors and media contacts are on LinkedIn too. If you ever want to be featured in an article, invited onto a podcast, or considered for a speaking engagement, LinkedIn is where those people are looking for interesting voices and expert perspectives. Journalists, podcast hosts, and event organizers actively search LinkedIn for guests and sources. Having a strong presence means you get found when those opportunities are circulating.</p>
<p>Understanding your audience on LinkedIn is the foundation of everything else in this course. The content you create, the connections you pursue, the way you write your profile, all of it should be built around the specific people you want to reach. As we move through the modules, you are going to get very clear on exactly who you are talking to on this platform, and that clarity is going to make every piece of your LinkedIn strategy sharper and more effective.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write out a one-sentence description of your ideal LinkedIn connection: who they are, what they do, what they struggle with, and what they are trying to build or solve.</li>
  <li>Use LinkedIn''s search bar to search for job titles related to your ideal client. Browse 10 profiles and notice what their activity looks like, what they post about, and what kinds of content they engage with.</li>
  <li>List three types of referral partners for your business who are likely on LinkedIn. Search for them and note how active they appear to be on the platform.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 2);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'The LinkedIn Algorithm and How to Work With It (Not Against It)',
'<p>One of the most common complaints I hear from entrepreneurs about LinkedIn is that they posted something and nobody saw it. And the frustration is real. But most of the time, it is not that the platform does not work. It is that the post was not set up to work with how the algorithm distributes content. Understanding the basics of the LinkedIn algorithm is going to change how you approach every post you write.</p>
<p>LinkedIn''s algorithm prioritizes content based on a few key signals. The first one is early engagement. When you post something, LinkedIn shows it to a small subset of your connections and followers first. If those people engage, meaning they like, comment, or share, within the first 60 to 90 minutes, the algorithm reads that as a signal that the content is worth distributing more widely. If nobody engages in that window, the post essentially stops being shown to new people. This means timing your posts and engaging with comments immediately after posting is not optional. It is part of the strategy.</p>
<p>The second signal is relevance. LinkedIn uses what people have engaged with in the past to decide what to put in their feed going forward. If your audience regularly engages with content about entrepreneurship, leadership, or small business growth, and your content fits those themes, the algorithm is more likely to surface your posts to them. This is why niching down your content to consistent themes makes you more visible, not less.</p>
<p>Comments are weighted more heavily than likes. A post with 30 thoughtful comments is going to outperform a post with 200 likes and 2 comments every single time. This is not accidental. LinkedIn designed it that way because comments signal real conversation, not just passive scrolling. When you write a post, you want to invite a response. A question at the end of a post, a prompt that asks people to share their experience, or a statement that invites a disagreement will always do better than a post that just states information with no invitation to respond.</p>
<p>Hashtags still matter on LinkedIn, but they work differently than on Instagram. You do not need 30 hashtags. Three to five well-chosen hashtags that are relevant to your topic and your audience are enough. LinkedIn users can follow hashtags, so using the right ones means your post can show up in the feed of people who do not follow you yet. Think about the hashtags your ideal client might actually follow. #entrepreneurship, #smallbusiness, #leadership, #womenentrepreneurs, and #businessgrowth are popular ones. Find the ones that are specific enough to reach the right people but popular enough to actually get traffic.</p>
<p>Dwell time is something LinkedIn has been factoring in more recently. If someone stops scrolling and reads your post for 30 seconds, that is a positive signal. If they click "see more" to expand a longer post, that is an even stronger signal. This tells you that writing posts worth reading, posts that make someone actually slow down, is more valuable than writing short posts that get ignored quickly. Quality and substance outperform brevity on LinkedIn in a way that is very different from Twitter or Instagram.</p>
<p>Native content always wins over links to external sites. LinkedIn wants people to stay on LinkedIn, so when you post a link to an article, a podcast, or a website, the algorithm reduces that post''s distribution significantly. If you want to share a link, the best strategy is to put it in the first comment rather than in the post itself. Write a compelling post, then add the link in the comments and reference it at the bottom of the post. This keeps your post in the algorithm''s good graces while still getting people to your content.</p>
<p>Understanding these mechanics is not about gaming the system. It is about making sure the work you put into your content actually reaches people. You can write a brilliant post and have almost nobody see it if you ignore the distribution signals. Once you understand how the algorithm works, you can create with both quality and visibility in mind, and that combination is what builds real traction on the platform.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Look at your last three LinkedIn posts (or if you have not posted recently, look at three posts from someone in your industry who is active). Identify whether the post had a question or prompt at the end that invited engagement.</li>
  <li>Pick three to five hashtags that are relevant to your business and your ideal client. Search each one on LinkedIn and confirm there is an active following for each one before you commit to using them regularly.</li>
  <li>Schedule your next post to go live during a time when your audience is most likely online. For most business audiences, Tuesday through Thursday between 8 and 10 AM or noon to 1 PM in your time zone tends to perform best.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 3);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Setting Your LinkedIn Goal Before You Do Anything Else',
'<p>Here is a mistake that kills a lot of LinkedIn strategies before they even start: jumping in without knowing what you actually want the platform to do for your business. People start posting, connecting, and engaging, but three months later they look up and do not know if any of it worked. That is because they never defined what "working" looks like for them. Before you build your profile, write your first post, or send your first connection request, you need to get clear on your specific goal for LinkedIn.</p>
<p>There are a few different goals LinkedIn can serve for entrepreneurs, and they each require slightly different approaches. The first is lead generation: using LinkedIn to find potential clients, start conversations, and move people into your sales process. This goal requires an optimized profile, a very intentional content strategy, and consistent outreach. The second goal is authority building: positioning yourself as an expert so that when people encounter your name, they already trust you before they ever reach out. This is a longer game but it compounds over time in a way that paid ads do not. The third goal is partnership development: building relationships with other businesses, referral sources, or collaborators who can grow your business without you being in every conversation. And the fourth is visibility for a specific opportunity, whether that is a speaking engagement, a press feature, investor attention, or a major contract.</p>
<p>Most entrepreneurs will have more than one of these goals, and that is fine. But one of them needs to be primary. Your primary goal shapes everything from the keywords in your headline to the topics you write about to the people you choose to connect with. If your primary goal is lead generation, you need to be connecting with potential clients, not just people you already know. If your primary goal is authority building, your content needs to go deeper and teach more. If it is partnership development, your outreach language is going to be different from how you would approach a potential client.</p>
<p>Let me also talk about time horizon, because LinkedIn is not a platform where you post twice and get a client. It is a compounding asset. The people who see the most results on LinkedIn typically committed to six months of consistent activity before they felt like the platform was "working." That is not a long time when you think about it. Six months of intentional activity versus years of sporadic posting with no strategy. The ones who stick with a clear goal for six months almost always see results. The ones who quit after six weeks almost never do.</p>
<p>Your goal also needs a number attached to it. Not vague like "more clients" but specific like "five discovery calls per month from LinkedIn" or "one media feature per quarter where someone found me through LinkedIn" or "two new referral partner relationships from LinkedIn each quarter." A number gives you something to measure. It lets you know when the strategy is working and when it needs to be adjusted. Without it, you are just guessing.</p>
<p>Once you have your goal and your number, you can reverse-engineer what needs to happen. If you want five discovery calls a month from LinkedIn and you know from experience that roughly one in five conversations leads to a call, you need to start 25 meaningful conversations per month. That is about one per day on weekdays. That is manageable. That is a plan. Compare that to "I will post and see what happens," which is not a plan at all.</p>
<p>This lesson is short on instructions because the work is mostly thinking. But the thinking matters more than almost anything else you will do in this course. Entrepreneurs who skip this step tend to spend months on LinkedIn and then walk away frustrated. The ones who start with a clear goal tend to look back in six months and be genuinely surprised by how much ground they covered. Do not skip it.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write down your single primary LinkedIn goal from the four options: lead generation, authority building, partnership development, or visibility for a specific opportunity.</li>
  <li>Attach a specific number to that goal. What does success look like in six months, measured as a number?</li>
  <li>Write two to three sentences describing the type of person on LinkedIn who, if they saw your content consistently, would help you hit that goal. This is your target audience on LinkedIn, and everything in this course should be built around reaching them.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 4);

