INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Your Headline Is Your Billboard. Make It Count.',
'<p>Your LinkedIn headline is the first thing anyone sees when they find your profile, when you comment on a post, when you send a connection request, and when you show up in search results. It is 220 characters of pure opportunity, and most people waste it by writing their job title. "Founder at XYZ Company" or "CEO | Business Owner | Speaker" tells someone nothing about why they should care. Your headline is not a label. It is a promise. It should communicate exactly who you help, what you help them do, and why that matters.</p>
<p>Here is a formula that works for most entrepreneurs: what you do, plus who you do it for, plus the result they get. So instead of "Business Coach," you write "I help first-generation entrepreneurs build profitable businesses without losing themselves in the process." Instead of "Marketing Consultant," you write "I build content systems that help service businesses generate leads without paid ads." You see the difference immediately. The second version makes someone say, "Wait, that is me. Tell me more." The first version gets scrolled past in half a second.</p>
<p>Your headline should also include relevant keywords because LinkedIn is a search engine. When someone searches for "business coach for women" or "financial consultant for entrepreneurs," LinkedIn surfaces profiles whose headlines and content include those terms. Think about what your ideal client would actually type into the search bar when they are looking for someone like you. Those words belong in your headline. You can write a compelling, human-sounding headline that still includes the right keywords. Those two things are not in conflict.</p>
<p>One thing to avoid in your headline is buzzwords that do not actually mean anything. "Passionate," "results-driven," "dynamic," and "visionary" are words everyone uses and nobody believes. They fill up character space that could be used for something concrete and specific. The more specific you are, the more trustworthy you sound, and the more clearly you signal that you know exactly what you do and who you do it for.</p>
<p>If you serve more than one audience or offer more than one type of service, your headline should prioritize the one that is most aligned with your LinkedIn goal. You can address everything else on the rest of your profile. The headline needs to do one job really well: make the right person stop and want to learn more about you. Trying to do too much in 220 characters usually means doing nothing particularly well.</p>
<p>Let me give you a few examples across different business types so you can see how this applies. A real estate investor focused on working with small business owners to build real estate as part of their wealth strategy might write: "I help small business owners use real estate to build wealth outside their business." A corporate consultant who helps teams perform better might write: "I help leadership teams stop losing their best people to toxic culture." A fitness professional targeting entrepreneurs might write: "I build sustainable health systems for founders who have tried everything and still feel exhausted." Each one of these is specific, clear, and makes the right person feel seen.</p>
<p>Your headline is not permanent. Test it. Write one version, use it for 30 days, and pay attention to whether people mention it in conversations, whether your profile views increase, and whether the people reaching out are the right ones. Then adjust. LinkedIn lets you change your headline as often as you want, and the best LinkedIn strategies treat it like a living part of the profile rather than something you set once and forget.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write your current headline down, then rewrite it using the formula: what you do, who you do it for, and the result they get. Aim for two to three versions so you can choose the strongest one.</li>
  <li>Identify two to three keywords your ideal client would search to find someone like you. Make sure at least one of those keywords appears in your new headline.</li>
  <li>Update your LinkedIn headline to your new version today. Do not wait until the profile is "perfect." The headline is the highest-leverage change you can make right now.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 1);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'The About Section — Writing Your Story Without Losing Your Audience',
'<p>The About section on LinkedIn is the most underused real estate on the entire platform. Most people either leave it blank, paste in their resume, or write a paragraph that sounds like it was written about them by someone they do not actually know. "Sarah is a results-driven professional with 10 years of experience in..." — that is not a profile that makes someone pick up the phone. The About section is where you get to speak directly to the person reading, build real trust, and make a clear case for why they should work with you, follow you, or reach out.</p>
<p>The first thing to know about the About section is that only the first two to three lines show before LinkedIn cuts off with a "see more" link. Those first lines need to pull someone in so they click to read the rest. Start with something specific, true, and interesting. Not a summary of your career. Not a list of your credentials. A sentence or two that names the problem your audience faces, describes the person you serve, or opens with a truth that makes the right person nod and think, "Yes. That is exactly it."</p>
<p>For example, instead of starting with "I have been a marketing consultant for 12 years," start with something like: "Most small business owners are doing a ton of marketing work and getting almost no return on it. Not because they are doing it wrong, but because nobody taught them how the pieces are supposed to connect." That kind of opening makes a potential client stop scrolling. It makes them feel understood. And it makes them want to know what you are going to say next.</p>
<p>After your opening, the About section should move through a few key elements. First, who you help and what problem you solve. Be specific. "Entrepreneurs" is broad. "First-generation business owners who built a business by working hard but now feel stuck and are not sure how to get to the next level" is specific. The more precisely you describe your person, the more that person feels like you are talking directly to them, and that feeling of being understood is what builds trust online. Second, how you help them. What is your approach? What makes the way you work different? You do not need to give away your whole methodology, but a few sentences about your process, philosophy, or approach help someone understand what it would be like to work with you.</p>
<p>Third, establish credibility without bragging. You can mention years of experience, the number of clients you have worked with, notable results you have produced, or relevant background that makes you qualified to do what you do. The key is to frame it as relevant to the reader rather than impressive for its own sake. "I have worked with over 200 entrepreneurs" is useful. "I am a sought-after expert" is not. Let the facts speak.</p>
<p>Fourth, make it personal enough to be human. The About section is where you can briefly mention why this work matters to you. Not a full life story, but a sentence or two that shows there is a real person behind the profile with real reasons for doing this work. People buy from people they trust, and they trust people who are willing to be a little bit real. You do not have to be vulnerable to be authentic. Just be honest about why this matters to you.</p>
<p>Finally, end with a clear call to action. Tell the reader exactly what to do if they want to take the next step. Follow you. Send a message. Visit your website. Book a call. People need to be directed. "Feel free to reach out" is too vague. "If you are ready to stop guessing at your marketing and start building something that actually grows your business, send me a message and let''s talk" is clear and inviting.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write the first three lines of your About section using an opening that names the problem your audience faces or describes the person you serve. Do not start with your name or your title.</li>
  <li>Rewrite or write your full About section including: who you help, how you help them, two to three credibility facts, one personal sentence about why this work matters to you, and a clear call to action. Keep it between 300 and 500 words.</li>
  <li>Update your LinkedIn About section today.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 2);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Profile Sections That Most Entrepreneurs Skip (But Shouldn''t)',
'<p>Most people build their LinkedIn profile by filling in the obvious fields: headline, about section, current job title, past experience. And then they stop. But there are several sections of your LinkedIn profile that are doing serious work in the background, either building your credibility or leaving gaps that make visitors less likely to reach out. In this lesson, we are going to walk through the sections that entrepreneurs consistently overlook and explain exactly why each one matters.</p>
<p>The Featured section sits near the top of your profile and is one of the first things people scroll to after reading your headline and the top of your About section. This is where you can pin your most important content: a lead magnet, a link to your website, a recent article that showcases your expertise, a video introduction, or a post that got a lot of traction. Think of this as a curated gallery of your best work. Most entrepreneurs leave it empty. Filling it with two or three strong pieces immediately signals that you are active, credible, and have something to offer.</p>
<p>The Services section is something that LinkedIn added relatively recently and that very few entrepreneurs take advantage of. If you offer services, you can list them directly on your profile so that when someone visits, they immediately see what you do. This is especially valuable if your headline is more brand-focused and less service-specific. The Services section also makes you appear in LinkedIn''s service provider search results, which is a separate discovery channel from the regular algorithm. It takes five minutes to set up and can bring in organic inquiries from people who are actively looking for someone who does what you do.</p>
<p>Recommendations are one of the most powerful credibility signals on LinkedIn, and most entrepreneurs either have none or have a few outdated ones from years ago. A recommendation is different from a skill endorsement. It is a written testimonial from a real client, colleague, or partner who can speak to the quality of your work. Three to five strong, specific recommendations on your profile tell a potential client that real people have worked with you and valued the experience enough to write about it publicly. If you do not have recommendations yet, reaching out to past clients and asking them to write one is one of the highest-return activities you can do on LinkedIn today.</p>
<p>The Skills section matters more than most people think, but not in the way most people use it. LinkedIn''s search algorithm uses skills to surface profiles in relevant searches, so adding skills that your ideal client would associate with the work you do matters. The catch is that LinkedIn also lets your connections endorse your skills, and a skill with 50 endorsements carries more algorithmic weight than one with two. Focus on five to ten skills that are genuinely central to your work and relevant to how your clients think about what they need.</p>
<p>The Experience section is worth treating differently than a resume. Instead of just listing your title and dates, write two to three sentences for each role that describe what you accomplished, who you served, and what impact you had. This is especially important for your current business. A lot of entrepreneurs write "Founder, XYZ Company" with no description, which tells the reader nothing. Treat each experience entry as another opportunity to show your credibility and communicate the value you bring.</p>
<p>Finally, do not overlook your profile photo and background banner. Your photo should be professional, clear, and current. It should look like you. A blurry photo, a photo where you are cropped out of a group, or a photo from five years ago all send the wrong signals. Your background banner is the large image behind your profile photo, and most people have the default blue LinkedIn banner. Replacing it with something that reflects your brand, your business, or your areas of focus is a simple visual signal that you take your LinkedIn presence seriously.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Add or update your Featured section with at least two items: your website and one piece of content (an article, a post, or a video) that showcases your expertise.</li>
  <li>Set up or update your Services section if you offer services. List at least three of your primary offerings.</li>
  <li>Reach out to two past clients or partners today and ask them to write a LinkedIn recommendation for you. Make it easy for them by suggesting what to focus on.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 3);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Optimizing for Search So the Right People Find You',
'<p>Here is something that changes how a lot of entrepreneurs think about LinkedIn: it is a search engine. Just like Google, people type things into the LinkedIn search bar and look at what comes up. They search for professionals in specific industries, people with specific expertise, service providers in certain locations, and consultants who work with specific types of clients. If your profile is not optimized for search, you are essentially invisible in those results, even though the people looking might be exactly who you want to reach.</p>
<p>LinkedIn search optimization starts with keywords. You need to know what words your ideal client would use to search for someone like you, and then you need to make sure those words appear throughout your profile. The headline and About section carry the most weight for search purposes, but your Experience section, Skills section, and even your posts contribute to how LinkedIn categorizes and surfaces your profile. If your ideal client is searching for "business coach for women entrepreneurs," then some version of those words needs to appear somewhere in your profile.</p>
<p>One thing that helps you identify the right keywords is searching on LinkedIn yourself. Search for your own job title or area of expertise and look at the profiles that come up first. What words do they use in their headlines? What skills have they listed? What language do they use in their About sections? You are not trying to copy their content, but you are getting a read on what the algorithm is already responding to for searches in your space. Pay attention to patterns in the language that keeps appearing across multiple strong profiles.</p>
<p>Location matters more than most entrepreneurs realize. LinkedIn allows people to search within a specific geographic area, and it factors location into search results even when someone does not explicitly filter by it. Make sure your location on your profile reflects where you actually want to do business. If you serve clients nationally but you are based in Tampa, keep Tampa as your location. That local signal helps you show up for local searches, and you can address your national reach in your About section or your headline.</p>
<p>Another way to boost your searchability is through consistent posting. When you post regularly about specific topics, LinkedIn indexes you as a creator in those topic areas. People who follow hashtags you use can discover your content. The algorithm begins to associate your profile with specific themes, which increases your chances of being surfaced to people who engage with similar content. Posting is not just an engagement strategy. It is a discovery strategy too.</p>
<p>LinkedIn also allows you to add contact information, a custom URL for your profile, and links to your website and other profiles. A custom URL (like linkedin.com/in/mirandajones rather than a string of random numbers) looks more professional and is easier to share. Adding your website gives visitors a next step and signals to LinkedIn that you have an established web presence beyond the platform. These are small details, but they contribute to both your credibility and your search visibility.</p>
<p>Finally, your LinkedIn profile is not a one-time setup. It is a living document that should be updated whenever something significant changes in your business, your offerings, or your focus. Every few months, read through your profile as if you are your ideal client and ask whether what you read makes you want to reach out. If the answer is not a clear yes, something needs to be updated. The entrepreneurs who treat their LinkedIn profile as an ongoing asset rather than a one-time task are the ones who see consistent results from the platform.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Identify the top five keywords your ideal client would use to search for someone like you. Make sure at least three of those keywords appear in your headline and About section.</li>
  <li>Update your LinkedIn URL to a custom URL that includes your name or business name. Go to your profile settings to do this if you have not already.</li>
  <li>Read through your entire profile from top to bottom as if you are a potential client. Identify any section that feels outdated, generic, or unclear. Update it before you move on to the next module.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 4);

