INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'The Types of Content That Work on LinkedIn (and Why)',
'<p>Let us talk content. Because this is where most entrepreneurs get stuck. They know they should post on LinkedIn, they sit down to write something, and then they stare at the screen because they do not know what to say. Or they post something that feels like it should be interesting and it gets seven likes, all from people they already know. The reason this happens is not that they are bad writers or that nobody cares about their industry. It is that they have not figured out the types of content that actually work on LinkedIn and why.</p>
<p>LinkedIn content falls into several categories, and understanding each one helps you build a mix that attracts the right people and keeps them engaged over time. The first category is insight-based content. This is where you share a perspective, an observation, or a piece of knowledge that is relevant to your audience''s world. It does not have to be a groundbreaking revelation. It just needs to be a real take on something your audience is thinking about. "Here is what I have learned after working with 100 small business owners about why most marketing does not convert" is insight-based content. It positions you as someone who has observed patterns and drawn conclusions that are worth hearing.</p>
<p>The second category is story-based content. LinkedIn audiences respond strongly to real stories, especially stories that show growth, challenge, or transformation. This does not mean you need to air every difficult moment publicly. It means you can share professional experiences, client wins (with permission), lessons from a mistake, or pivotal moments in your business journey in a way that connects emotionally while also delivering a practical insight. The combination of emotion plus lesson is one of the most powerful content formats on the platform.</p>
<p>The third category is practical "how-to" content. Step-by-step instructions, frameworks, checklists, processes, and tips that help your audience solve a specific problem. This type of content tends to get saved, shared, and referenced, which extends its reach over time. If you can teach something specific and useful in a LinkedIn post, the people who benefit from that teaching are going to remember you the next time they need what you offer.</p>
<p>The fourth category is questions and conversation starters. Sometimes the most engaging content on LinkedIn is the simplest: a genuine question directed at your audience. Not a rhetorical question, but a real one. "What is the one thing that changed the trajectory of your business? I want to hear from people who have been in it." Questions invite the comment section to become a discussion, and the algorithm loves that. Plus, the answers you get are often genuinely valuable for understanding what your audience is thinking about.</p>
<p>The fifth category is what I call validation content. These are posts that name something your audience is feeling or experiencing and validate that it makes sense. "If you have been inconsistent with your business development because you are exhausted from doing everything yourself, you are not lazy. You are overextended. Here is what actually helped me." Validation content builds loyalty because it makes people feel understood, not judged. In a world full of content that tells entrepreneurs what they should be doing, content that acknowledges the reality of what they are actually experiencing stands out.</p>
<p>The mix of these five types of content is what keeps your LinkedIn presence interesting over time. If you only ever post practical tips, your audience starts to feel like they are reading a textbook. If you only ever share stories, they might enjoy them but not think of you as an expert they can hire. Variety keeps people engaged, and engaged people become clients, referrals, and partners.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Look at your last five LinkedIn posts (or five posts from an entrepreneur you admire if you have not posted recently) and identify which category each one falls into: insight, story, practical how-to, question, or validation. Notice which types are missing.</li>
  <li>Write one sentence each for three different post ideas using three different content types. You do not have to write the full posts yet. Just the starting premise.</li>
  <li>Pick your best idea from those three and write a full draft. Save it for the lesson on actually writing and formatting posts.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 1);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'How to Write LinkedIn Posts That Get Read and Remembered',
'<p>Writing content for LinkedIn is a specific skill, and it is different from writing for Instagram, writing emails, or writing a blog post. LinkedIn audiences are skimming fast. They are in a business mindset, which means they are somewhat skeptical, somewhat distracted, and looking for a reason to either stop and read or keep scrolling. Your job as a content creator on this platform is to give them a reason to stop within the first line or two, and then reward that decision with something genuinely useful or interesting.</p>
<p>The opening line of a LinkedIn post is everything. LinkedIn cuts off your post with a "see more" prompt after the first two or three lines, which means your opening needs to do two things: be interesting enough to earn the click, and clearly signal what the post is about so the right people know it is for them. There are several types of opening lines that consistently work. A bold or counterintuitive statement: "Most LinkedIn advice is making entrepreneurs invisible." A specific number or fact: "I reviewed 50 LinkedIn profiles for entrepreneurs last month. Only 6 were actually working." A question: "What if the reason you are not getting clients from LinkedIn has nothing to do with your content?" A relatable frustration: "You posted something you thought was good and it got 11 likes. We have all been there."</p>
<p>After the opening, the structure of a LinkedIn post matters. Avoid writing in long paragraphs. LinkedIn is read on mobile more than desktop, and dense paragraphs look like walls of text on a phone screen. Short paragraphs of two to three sentences work best. Use line breaks frequently. Some of the highest-performing posts on LinkedIn are written almost entirely in single-sentence lines. The white space is not emptiness. It is readability.</p>
<p>Specificity makes posts believable and memorable. "I helped a client grow her revenue" is forgettable. "I helped a health coach in Atlanta go from 12 discovery calls a month to 43 in 90 days by changing two things about her LinkedIn content strategy" is specific enough to be credible and interesting. You do not have to reveal the client''s name. But the details make the story real, and real stories stick.</p>
<p>Every post should have a point of view. Not just information, but a perspective. LinkedIn is full of posts that state obvious facts: "Consistency is important in business." Nobody is going to stop scrolling for that. But "Consistency is the most overrated piece of advice in business, and here is what actually matters more" is a post that immediately creates tension and makes someone want to read on. You are allowed to have opinions. You are allowed to disagree with conventional wisdom. You are allowed to say something that not everyone will agree with. That is what makes content interesting.</p>
<p>End your post with something that invites a response. Not always a question, but something that opens the door to conversation. "I would love to know what has worked for you. Drop it in the comments." Or "If this resonated, share it with a founder you know who needs to hear it." Or simply a statement that acknowledges the reader: "If you are in this place right now, this is your reminder that the gap is normal and it does not mean you are behind." These endings turn a post into a conversation rather than a broadcast, and conversation is what the algorithm rewards.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write three different opening lines for a post using three different formats: a bold statement, a specific number or fact, and a relatable frustration. Pick the strongest one.</li>
  <li>Take a post you have already written or the draft you created in the last lesson and reformat it with shorter paragraphs, line breaks, and no paragraph longer than two to three sentences.</li>
  <li>Add a closing line to that same post that invites a specific response from your audience.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 2);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'How Often to Post and How to Build a Content System You Will Actually Stick To',
'<p>Here is the truth about posting on LinkedIn: consistency over time matters more than any single post you will ever write. The entrepreneurs who see real results from LinkedIn are not the ones who went viral once. They are the ones who showed up reliably, week after week, month after month, until the algorithm trusted them enough to surface their content regularly and their audience trusted them enough to think of them when a need arose. Consistency is the strategy. Everything else is tactics.</p>
<p>But consistency is only possible if you have a system. Trying to think of what to post every morning and then sit down and write it is a recipe for inconsistency. Life gets in the way. Business gets in the way. Posting feels optional, and optional things get dropped when things get busy. What you need instead is a content system that makes creating posts easier and faster, that gives you ideas before you run out of them, and that removes as many decision points as possible so you can just execute.</p>
<p>The first part of the system is batching. Instead of writing one post per day, set aside one block of time per week, or even per month, and write multiple posts in one sitting. When you are already in writing mode, it is much faster to write four posts than it is to write one post four times on four different days. Most entrepreneurs who post consistently have a backlog of drafts that they can pull from when they sit down to post. They are never starting from zero on the day they post.</p>
<p>The second part of the system is a topic bank. This is a running list of ideas, observations, lessons, stories, and questions that you capture whenever they come to you. When you have a client conversation that produces a great insight, write it down. When something happens in your business that teaches you something, write it down. When you read something that sparks a reaction, write it down. The topic bank means you never sit down to write without ideas. You are pulling from a pool rather than generating from nothing.</p>
<p>For posting frequency, I want to give you a real recommendation rather than a vague "be consistent" answer. For most entrepreneurs, three times per week is the sweet spot. It is enough to stay visible to your audience and keep the algorithm''s attention without becoming so frequent that quality suffers. If three times a week feels like too much right now, start with two. But commit to two. Put it in your calendar like a meeting. If you can only do one post a week, do one post a week, but do it every single week without fail. The frequency matters less than the reliability.</p>
<p>Comments on other people''s posts are part of your content strategy too, even though they are not posts you write on your own profile. Leaving thoughtful, substantive comments on posts from your ideal clients, your peers, and your referral partners is one of the fastest ways to grow your visibility on LinkedIn. When you comment on a post, everyone who sees that post also sees your name and headline. If your comment is smart and relevant, some of those people will click on your profile. Ten good comments a day can drive more traffic to your profile than one mediocre post per day.</p>
<p>Repurposing content is a legitimate and smart strategy. A lesson you teach in your course, a chapter from your book, a framework you explained in a client presentation, an idea from a workshop you facilitated — all of these can become LinkedIn posts. You do not have to create everything from scratch. In fact, the ideas that your real work is built on are often your best LinkedIn content, because they are the ideas you know deeply and believe in genuinely.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Block time on your calendar this week for a one-hour content batching session. Your only goal for that session is to write five LinkedIn post drafts.</li>
  <li>Start your topic bank. Open a notes app, a Google Doc, or a dedicated notebook and write down 10 post ideas right now: lessons from your work, observations about your industry, stories from your own business journey, and questions you genuinely want to ask your audience.</li>
  <li>Commit to a specific posting frequency for the next 90 days and write it down as a commitment to yourself. Then put each scheduled posting day in your calendar.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 3);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Using LinkedIn Articles, Newsletters, and Video to Expand Your Reach',
'<p>Beyond regular posts, LinkedIn offers additional content formats that can significantly expand your reach and deepen your authority. Most entrepreneurs stick to text posts and miss these other formats entirely. Understanding when and why to use them adds another dimension to your LinkedIn presence and helps you reach different segments of your audience in ways that text posts alone cannot.</p>
<p>LinkedIn Articles are long-form pieces, similar to blog posts, that live on your profile permanently and can be discovered through LinkedIn search as well as through Google search. Unlike a regular post that has a lifespan of a few days in the algorithm, an article stays accessible indefinitely. This makes articles ideal for content that you want to serve as a reference: comprehensive guides, detailed frameworks, your perspective on an important industry issue, or a deep dive into a topic that your audience returns to repeatedly. Articles are indexed by search engines, which means someone could find your LinkedIn article through a Google search even if they are not on LinkedIn. That is additional discoverability that a regular post cannot give you.</p>
<p>LinkedIn Newsletter is a feature that lets you publish regular articles to subscribers who have opted in to receive them as notifications. This is different from your regular post feed because subscribers get a direct notification when you publish, which means your newsletter goes straight to their attention rather than competing in the general feed algorithm. LinkedIn Newsletters have been a significant growth lever for entrepreneurs and thought leaders because they function almost like an email list within the platform. If you are thinking about building a newsletter audience, starting a LinkedIn Newsletter is a lower-friction entry point than building an email list from scratch, though the long-term goal should be to eventually move those subscribers to your email list where you have more control.</p>
<p>Video is one of the highest-engagement content formats on LinkedIn right now, and it is still underused relative to text posts. This gives you an advantage if you are willing to get in front of the camera. LinkedIn users are not expecting polished, professionally produced videos. In fact, the authentic and slightly rough look of videos recorded on a phone often performs better than highly produced content because it feels real. Short videos of two to five minutes that teach something specific, share a genuine moment, or give a perspective on something relevant to your audience can dramatically increase your profile views and connection requests.</p>
<p>You do not have to use all of these formats at once. Start with text posts and get consistent there first. Then, once you have a rhythm, experiment with one additional format. If you are a strong writer, add a monthly LinkedIn Article. If you love talking and teaching, add a video once a week or once every two weeks. If you want to build a dedicated subscriber base, launch a LinkedIn Newsletter with a clear value proposition for what people will get from subscribing. The goal is to have a content presence that is active and multi-dimensional without becoming overwhelming to manage.</p>
<p>One thing worth noting about all LinkedIn content: whatever you create, repurpose it. An article can become three or four LinkedIn posts. A video can be summarized in a text post. A newsletter issue can be shared as a post with a link to the full article. You are not doing more work with repurposing. You are doing the same work and getting more mileage out of it. This is how the entrepreneurs who seem to be everywhere on LinkedIn actually manage it: they are not creating more content. They are getting more out of every piece they create.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Look at a key insight or framework from your business that you explain regularly to clients. This is probably your best LinkedIn Article topic. Write a working title and a short outline for it.</li>
  <li>Decide which additional content format you want to experiment with first: article, newsletter, or video. Write one sentence about why that format fits your business and your strengths.</li>
  <li>Film a one to two minute video on your phone about one thing you want your ideal client to know. You do not have to post it yet. Just practice. Notice how it feels and what you want to improve.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 4);

