VALUES (v_course_id, 'Building the Right Connections (Not Just a Big Number)', 4)
RETURNING id INTO v_mod_id;

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Quality vs. Quantity — Why 500 Right Connections Beat 5,000 Wrong Ones',
'<p>There is a number that LinkedIn used to display on every profile: 500+. Once you hit 500 connections, LinkedIn stops counting publicly and just shows "500+." Because of this, a lot of people treated 500 connections like a milestone, and the connection number became a badge of status. And then the platform got flooded with people connecting with everyone they could find, building massive networks full of strangers who had nothing to do with their business, and wondering why their LinkedIn strategy was not working.</p>
<p>Here is the truth: connection count is one of the least important metrics on LinkedIn for entrepreneurs. What matters is whether the people in your network are aligned with what you do, who you serve, and what you are trying to build. A network of 500 decision-makers in your ideal client category is worth infinitely more than a network of 5,000 random professionals. The reason comes down to how the algorithm distributes your content. Your posts are shown primarily to your first-degree connections. If those connections are not your target audience, your content is disappearing into a room full of people who will never buy from you, refer you, or open a door for you.</p>
<p>Think of your LinkedIn network like a community. The people in that community are going to see your content, engage with it, and form opinions about you based on what you consistently show up and share. You want that community to be full of the people you actually want to serve and work with. That means being intentional about who you connect with from the start, and it means being willing to be selective even when LinkedIn is suggesting you connect with someone who has nothing to do with your business.</p>
<p>That said, there is a nuance here. Your network is not just your ideal clients. It is also referral partners, peers, mentors, collaborators, and community members who can amplify your work or open doors even if they are never going to buy from you themselves. Think in concentric circles. In the inner circle: potential clients and current clients. In the next circle: referral sources and strategic partners. In the next: peers and fellow entrepreneurs who are going through similar things. And in the outer circle: creators and thought leaders who shape conversations in your space. All of these connections serve a purpose. What you want to avoid is filling your network with people who do not fit into any of these circles.</p>
<p>One practical note: when you connect with someone on LinkedIn, you have the option to send a personalized message with the request. Most people send the default connection request with no message, which is essentially saying "I clicked a button." Sending a short, specific, personalized note dramatically increases your acceptance rate and, more importantly, starts the relationship on a better footing. We will cover what to actually say in these notes in the next lesson, but for now, commit to never sending a blank connection request again.</p>
<p>The other piece of this that most entrepreneurs overlook is that your existing network is already your asset. The 200 or 500 or 1,000 connections you already have include people who do not know the full picture of what you do. Part of building the right network is showing up consistently enough with clear enough content that the people already in your network start to actually understand how you help people. You might already have your next client in your network. They just have not seen enough from you yet to reach out.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Open your LinkedIn connections and scroll through. Identify five to ten people in your current network who are clearly aligned with your business, whether as ideal clients, referral partners, or strategic allies. Make a plan to engage with their content this week.</li>
  <li>Set a personal filter for future connections. Write down three criteria a person should meet for you to connect with them on LinkedIn: they work in a certain industry, they hold a certain role, they are in a certain stage of business, or they have a specific type of problem you help solve.</li>
  <li>Find 10 people on LinkedIn today who meet your connection criteria. Save their profiles or note their names. You will send connection requests in the next lesson.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 1);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'How to Connect With People Without Being Spammy or Weird About It',
'<p>The fear of coming across as spammy stops a lot of entrepreneurs from doing any outreach at all on LinkedIn. And honestly, that fear makes sense. LinkedIn inboxes are full of terrible outreach messages. The moment someone accepts a connection request, they get hit with a pitch. "Hi [First Name], I noticed your profile and I think you would be a perfect fit for our [product/service/event]." Delete. Block. The message goes into a mental folder labeled "why LinkedIn is the worst."</p>
<p>The reason those messages fail is not because outreach does not work. It is because the person doing the outreach is starting with what they want rather than what the other person might find valuable. Good outreach on LinkedIn is relationship-first, not pitch-first. And the difference between relationship-first and pitch-first outreach is not complicated. It is just a different mindset about what you are trying to accomplish.</p>
<p>When you send a connection request, your goal is to start a relationship, not close a sale. Your connection note should be short, specific, and genuine. Mention something specific: you read their post and it resonated, you are in the same industry or space and wanted to be connected, you have a mutual connection you both respect, or you heard them speak somewhere. The specificity signals that you are a real person who actually paid attention, not a bot spraying connection requests. "I came across your post about hiring your first team member. I am in a similar stage and the way you broke it down was really helpful. Would love to be connected" is a connection request that gets accepted. "I think there may be synergies between our businesses" is a connection request that gets ignored.</p>
<p>After someone accepts your request, wait. Do not send a sales message immediately. Do not send any message at all if you do not have something genuine and valuable to say. Engage with their content instead. Like a post. Leave a thoughtful comment. Share something they wrote with a note about why it is worth reading. Do this for a few weeks. Build actual familiarity before you send a message asking for anything.</p>
<p>When you do eventually send a message, make it about them, not you. Ask a genuine question about something they have posted about. Share a resource that is actually relevant to something they are working on. Offer a perspective or insight on a problem you know they are dealing with. The goal of the first message is not to convert them into a client. The goal is to get them to respond and to begin a real conversation. That conversation, over time, naturally creates opportunities for you to offer your help, which is where clients actually come from.</p>
<p>There are situations where a more direct outreach makes sense: following up with someone you met in person, reconnecting with a past client or contact who has gone quiet, or reaching out to someone who has engaged repeatedly with your content and clearly sees the value of what you do. In those situations, you have already established some context and trust, and a more direct message does not feel out of place. The context is what makes the difference. Without it, directness feels pushy. With it, directness feels helpful.</p>
<p>One more thing worth saying: volume is not the answer. Sending 50 connection requests a day and following them all up with a template message is not a LinkedIn strategy. It is digital spam. Twenty well-targeted, genuinely personalized connection requests per week, followed by real relationship-building behavior, will produce more clients than 500 generic ones. Quality of outreach, not quantity, is what moves the needle for entrepreneurs on this platform.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Write a template connection note that feels personal and genuine. It should have a fill-in-the-blank for something specific about the person but otherwise feel like something you would actually write. Keep it under 200 characters (LinkedIn''s limit for connection notes).</li>
  <li>Send five connection requests today to people from the list you made in the last lesson. Use your personalized connection note for each one, customized to each person.</li>
  <li>Identify three people in your existing network who have been engaging with your content or who you have wanted to reconnect with. Send each of them a genuine message this week that starts a real conversation.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 2);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Engaging With Content as a Growth Strategy',
'<p>Here is a LinkedIn growth strategy that most people underestimate: commenting. Not liking. Not sharing (though those matter too). Commenting. Writing real, substantive, thoughtful responses to other people''s posts is one of the fastest ways to grow your visibility on LinkedIn, and it costs you nothing except a few minutes of attention.</p>
<p>When you leave a comment on someone''s post, your name and headline appear under that post. Everyone who sees the post also sees your comment. If the post has significant reach, meaning hundreds or thousands of people are viewing it, your comment is appearing in front of all of those people too. And if your comment is genuinely interesting, adds to the conversation, or shares a perspective that resonates, those people click on your name to see who you are. That is profile traffic generated by a comment, not by your own post.</p>
<p>The key word is genuinely interesting. A comment that says "Great post! So true!" is not going to make anyone click on your profile. In fact, it might make them think less of you. But a comment that adds a real perspective, shares a relevant example from your own experience, challenges the premise thoughtfully, or extends the idea with something new is a comment that makes people curious about you. Think of your comments as mini-posts: they should have a point of view and stand on their own as worthwhile contributions to the conversation.</p>
<p>Engaging consistently with the content of people you want to be connected to is also one of the best ways to build a real relationship with them before you ever send a direct message. If you comment thoughtfully on someone''s posts three or four times over the course of a few weeks, they start to recognize your name. When you eventually do send a connection request or a direct message, you are not a stranger anymore. You are someone they have noticed. That changes the entire dynamic of the outreach.</p>
<p>Comment targeting is a strategic activity, not a random one. Decide whose posts you want to engage with regularly. Your list should include: potential clients who are active on LinkedIn, referral partners in your space, peers and collaborators, and thought leaders who attract the kind of audience you want to be in front of. Spend 10 to 15 minutes per day on LinkedIn focused specifically on leaving quality comments on these people''s posts. Over 90 days, this single habit can generate more relationship capital than almost anything else you do on the platform.</p>
<p>Engaging with comments on your own posts is just as important as commenting on others''. When someone takes the time to comment on your content, respond to them. Not with a one-word "thank you" but with a real response that continues the conversation. This does two things: it signals to the algorithm that your post is generating engagement (which extends its distribution), and it shows your audience that you are actually present and paying attention. People want to know there is a real human behind the content. Responding to comments is how you show them there is.</p>
<p>Shares are a form of engagement too, and they carry significant weight. When you share someone''s post with a genuine note about why it is worth reading, you are doing something generous for that person and something valuable for your own audience. It is a different kind of relationship-building than a comment, but it is powerful in its own way. The people whose content you share notice it. It starts conversations. And it positions you as someone who is genuinely engaged with the broader community in your space, not just broadcasting your own content.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Make a list of 10 people on LinkedIn whose content you want to engage with regularly. Include a mix of potential clients, referral partners, and thought leaders in your space.</li>
  <li>Spend 20 minutes today leaving substantive comments on at least five posts from people on your list. Each comment should be at least two to three sentences and add a genuine perspective.</li>
  <li>Go back to your most recent post and respond to any comments you have not yet replied to. Make each response a real continuation of the conversation.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 3);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'LinkedIn Groups, Events, and Community Features',
'<p>LinkedIn is not just a feed of content and a database of profiles. It also has community features that are worth knowing about, especially for entrepreneurs who want to build relationships at scale and position themselves as connectors and leaders within their space. LinkedIn Groups, Events, and the collaborative article feature each offer different ways to expand your presence beyond your immediate network.</p>
<p>LinkedIn Groups are communities organized around specific topics, industries, or professional identities. Members of a group can post content within the group, start conversations, and engage with each other in a space that is more focused than the general feed. For entrepreneurs, groups offer a few specific opportunities. First, they are places where your ideal clients are gathering and discussing the problems you help solve. Joining those groups and participating authentically in conversations positions you as a resource and a knowledgeable voice in that space. Second, you can post within groups and reach members who are not in your direct network, which expands your visibility beyond your existing connections.</p>
<p>The quality of LinkedIn Groups varies widely. Some are active, well-moderated communities with real conversation happening. Others are ghost towns or spam repositories where nobody is engaging authentically. Before you invest time in a group, spend a few days observing it. Is there real discussion? Are the members your ideal clients or referral partners? Is the group growing or stagnating? Join the ones that are actually alive and opt out of the ones that are not.</p>
<p>LinkedIn Events let you create virtual or in-person events directly on the platform. If you host webinars, workshops, office hours, masterclasses, or any other kind of live event, creating it as a LinkedIn Event gives you a built-in RSVP system and the ability to notify attendees and followers. When someone RSVPs to your event on LinkedIn, LinkedIn notifies them before the event. The event also gets distributed in the feeds of your connections and can be discovered through search. If you are running events as part of your business or community-building strategy, LinkedIn Events is a free distribution channel you should be using.</p>
<p>LinkedIn collaborative articles are a newer feature where LinkedIn prompts professionals to contribute their perspective to AI-generated article frameworks on specific topics. If LinkedIn invites you to contribute, take the opportunity. Contributors who are selected get a "Top Voice" badge displayed on their profiles, which adds a credibility signal that shows up whenever your name appears on the platform. It is not available to everyone, but if you receive an invitation to contribute, it is worth taking five minutes to add your perspective.</p>
<p>LinkedIn Live is the platform''s live video feature. If you are comfortable with live video, LinkedIn Live can be a high-engagement format that gets significantly more reach than regular video posts because LinkedIn promotes live streams more aggressively in the feed. The catch is that you need to apply to use LinkedIn Live and the approval process takes time. If this is something you want to explore, apply now so you are approved by the time you are ready to use it.</p>
<p>The broader point of this lesson is that LinkedIn is a fuller ecosystem than most entrepreneurs use. The entrepreneurs who get the most out of the platform are the ones who engage with multiple features: regular posts, comments, direct messages, groups, events, and sometimes live video. You do not have to use all of them. But knowing what is available lets you choose the ones that fit your business and your strengths, and those tools can expand your reach in ways that posting alone cannot.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Search LinkedIn Groups for two or three groups related to your industry or your ideal client''s industry. Evaluate whether the groups are active and join any that have real, ongoing conversation.</li>
  <li>If you host any kind of live event, webinar, or workshop, create a LinkedIn Event for your next one. Share the link with your connections and invite your first 10 attendees.</li>
  <li>Explore the collaborative articles section of LinkedIn and see whether there are active contributions happening in topics related to your expertise. If you are invited to contribute, accept and add your perspective.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 4);

