RETURNING id INTO v_mod_id;

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'What Lead Generation on LinkedIn Actually Looks Like',
'<p>Let us be clear about something upfront: lead generation on LinkedIn is not about sending everyone a pitch the moment they accept your connection request. That approach has given LinkedIn a reputation as a place full of spammy salespeople, and if you have ever experienced the unsolicited pitch flood after connecting with someone, you understand why it puts people off so completely. Real lead generation on LinkedIn looks nothing like that. It is slower, more human, and far more effective in the long run.</p>
<p>Lead generation on LinkedIn is about moving people through a natural trust-building journey that ends with them being ready and eager to explore working with you. That journey has four stages. The first stage is visibility: the person is aware you exist because they have seen your name in the feed, seen a comment you left, or come across your profile in a search. The second stage is familiarity: they have seen you enough times with consistent, valuable content that they have a sense of who you are and what you stand for. The third stage is trust: they have seen enough to believe you know what you are talking about, and they have possibly had a direct interaction with you through comments or messages. The fourth stage is readiness: something in their business or life has created urgency around the problem you solve, and because they already trust you, you are the first person they think of.</p>
<p>Your LinkedIn strategy needs to serve all four stages simultaneously. Your content and your profile do the visibility and familiarity work. Your engagement, your direct messages, and your consistency do the trust work. The readiness stage you cannot control, but you can be positioned so that when someone hits that stage, you are already the person they think of.</p>
<p>One of the most practical frameworks for lead generation on LinkedIn is what some people call the "give, give, give, ask" model. For every three to four interactions you have with someone, whether those interactions are comments on their posts, genuine conversations, sharing their content, or direct messages with something valuable, you earn the right to mention what you do or make an offer. This is not a rigid formula. It is a mindset. Relationships precede transactions, and the more value you put into the relationship before you ask for anything, the more natural and welcome your ask becomes.</p>
<p>The types of leads that LinkedIn generates tend to be higher quality than leads from many other channels because the relationship has been established before the inquiry ever happens. When someone reaches out to you on LinkedIn after following your content for months, they already know your perspective, your approach, and roughly how you work. They are not kicking the tires. They are ready to have a real conversation. That is the power of an authority-based lead generation strategy on this platform.</p>
<p>You also need to be clear about what you want people to do when they are ready to take a step. Do you want them to send you a direct message? Visit your website and book a call? Download a free resource that starts a nurture sequence? The pathway from LinkedIn connection to actual client should be designed, not accidental. We will talk in the next lesson about what that pathway looks like and how to build it into your LinkedIn presence so it works without you being in every interaction.</p>
<p>Lead generation on LinkedIn is not a sprint. If you go into it expecting clients within a week, you are going to be disappointed. But if you go into it with a six-month horizon and a commitment to consistent, value-driven activity, the results can be genuinely significant. The entrepreneurs I have seen build the most consistent pipelines from LinkedIn are the ones who treat it like a long-term relationship investment rather than a quick sales channel. That mindset shift is the foundation of everything in this module.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Map out your current LinkedIn presence against the four stages: visibility, familiarity, trust, readiness. Honestly assess which stage most of your audience is at. What is the gap you need to close?</li>
  <li>Write down the specific action you want a ready prospect to take when they are interested in working with you. Book a call? Send a DM? Download a resource? Make sure this action is clearly referenced somewhere in your profile.</li>
  <li>Identify five people in your current LinkedIn network who might be at the "trust" or "readiness" stage. Make a plan to have a real conversation with each of them this week.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 1);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'The LinkedIn Content Funnel — How Content Turns Strangers Into Clients',
'<p>One of the most powerful things you can do on LinkedIn is build a content funnel: a deliberate sequence of content types that moves someone from first encountering your name all the way to making an inquiry about working with you. This is not about manipulating people or engineering a false relationship. It is about being thoughtful and strategic so that the content you create does real business development work, not just accumulate likes.</p>
<p>The top of your content funnel is awareness content. This is content that reaches people who do not know you yet. It is broad enough to be relevant to your target audience but specific enough to signal your expertise and perspective. A post that challenges a common misconception in your industry. A story about a transformation that happens when someone makes a particular shift in their business. A strong take on a trend that your audience is experiencing. This kind of content gets shared, gets comments from strangers, and brings new people into your orbit. The goal here is not conversion. It is discovery.</p>
<p>The middle of your content funnel is education and engagement content. This is where you go deeper on the topics you are known for. Detailed frameworks, step-by-step processes, case study breakdowns (with client permission), and nuanced perspectives on specific problems. This content serves two purposes: it shows the people who already know you that your expertise goes beyond a strong headline, and it starts to build the trust that makes people think of you as an expert they would actually hire. People at this stage of the funnel are reading your content regularly, saving your posts, and referencing your frameworks. They are not clients yet, but they are warm.</p>
<p>The bottom of the funnel is conversion content. This is content that is directly connected to the work you do and makes a clear invitation. A post about a client result that mentions you have one or two spots open. A post that describes exactly who your ideal client is and what happens when they work with you. A post that shares the specific transformation your program or service delivers, written so compellingly that the person reading it recognizes themselves in it and feels moved to reach out. Bottom-of-funnel content is not a hard sell. It is clarity. It tells the people who are ready exactly where to go.</p>
<p>Most entrepreneurs only create top-of-funnel content. They share broad, popular takes but never go deep enough to move people from "I like this person" to "I want to hire this person." The fix is to balance your content across all three funnel stages. A rough mix of roughly 60 percent awareness, 30 percent education and engagement, and 10 percent conversion content gives you a presence that is both attracting new people and moving existing followers toward a decision.</p>
<p>Your lead magnets, whether they are free resources, guides, assessments, or mini trainings, can also be integrated into your LinkedIn content funnel. A post that teaches something valuable and then invites people to download the full framework gives you both engagement and list-building in one move. A post that references a free assessment or quiz gives your audience something to take action on immediately. These touchpoints outside of LinkedIn (on your website or through your email list) are where you deepen the relationship and maintain contact with people who are ready to learn more.</p>
<p>The content funnel is not something you build once and walk away from. It is something you maintain through consistent posting across all three levels. Check in periodically to make sure you are not stuck in one type of content. If all you are doing is top-of-funnel awareness posts, push yourself to go deeper. If all you are doing is conversion posts, pull back and build more relationship. The balance is what keeps both your audience engaged and your pipeline full.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Review your last 10 LinkedIn posts and categorize each one as awareness, education and engagement, or conversion content. Note the balance. Are you missing one category entirely?</li>
  <li>Write one conversion-focused post. Describe a specific outcome your ideal client gets from working with you, name the type of person who gets that result, and end with a clear invitation to reach out or take a next step.</li>
  <li>Choose or create one lead magnet (a free guide, checklist, template, or resource) that you can reference in a LinkedIn post. Write the post and plan to include the link in the first comment.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 2);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Turning Conversations Into Discovery Calls and Clients',
'<p>The moment someone moves from engaging with your content to sending you a direct message is a significant moment. They have crossed from passive observer to active seeker. They are interested enough to initiate contact, which means something you have been doing on LinkedIn is working. How you handle that first message and the conversation that follows determines whether that interested person becomes a client or a missed opportunity.</p>
<p>First: respond quickly. People reach out when they are ready, and readiness is often fleeting. If someone sends you a message on Monday morning and you do not respond until Thursday, the moment has often passed. They have either figured out a solution elsewhere, talked themselves out of it, or simply lost momentum. If you are serious about generating leads from LinkedIn, treating your LinkedIn inbox like a business tool rather than a social notification means checking it at least once or twice a day and responding promptly to genuine inquiries.</p>
<p>When you respond, start with genuine curiosity. Ask a question. Find out more about their situation before you say anything about your services. "Tell me more about what is going on in your business" or "What made you reach out today?" are better opening responses than "Great to hear from you! Here are my services and pricing." The person who reached out wants to feel heard and understood, not processed. The conversation should feel like the beginning of a relationship, not the beginning of a sales script.</p>
<p>As the conversation develops and you understand their situation better, your goal is to qualify whether they are actually a good fit for what you do. This is not about being selective for the sake of being exclusive. It is about making sure you can actually help them before you invest in a longer conversation or propose a call. Ask about what they have tried before, what their goals are, and what specific challenge they are facing. Listen more than you talk. The more you understand their situation, the more relevant and compelling your response will be.</p>
<p>When the fit is clear, make the invitation to a call specific and easy. Do not say "Let me know if you ever want to chat." Say "Based on what you have shared, I think it would be worth getting on a 30-minute call to see if I can help. Here is a link to my calendar." A direct, confident invitation to a specific next step is more effective than a vague suggestion. People appreciate knowing exactly what happens next. Ambiguity creates friction, and friction kills momentum.</p>
<p>Not every conversation is going to turn into a client, and that is fine. Some conversations will reveal that the person is not a fit right now, is not financially ready, or is in a different place than they sounded. That is not a failed conversation. It is useful information, and it is still a relationship. The person who is not ready today might be ready in six months. The person who is not a fit for your main service might need your smallest offering. Treat every conversation as an investment in a relationship that might pay off in unexpected ways, even if it does not produce an immediate client.</p>
<p>Follow up after calls. If someone books a discovery call with you and you have a great conversation but they do not move forward, follow up once with something genuinely useful. Not a pressure message, but a resource, a perspective, or a check-in that shows you are still thinking about their situation. Some of the best clients come from those follow-up moments when someone felt stuck and then realized they were ready. LinkedIn conversations that continue over weeks and months are often the ones that produce the most loyal and highest-paying clients.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Review your LinkedIn inbox. Are there any conversations you let drop that are worth picking back up? Send a genuine follow-up message to two people you have not talked to in a while.</li>
  <li>Write your response to the most common first DM you get from interested potential clients. Make sure it starts with a question about their situation rather than a pitch about your services.</li>
  <li>Set up a free scheduling tool (Calendly, Acuity, or any equivalent) if you do not have one, and make sure the link is easy to send in a LinkedIn message. Practice including it naturally at the right moment in a conversation.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 3);

INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, content, video_url, position) VALUES (v_mod_id, 'Tracking What Is Working So You Can Do More of It',
'<p>Here is something entrepreneurs rarely do on LinkedIn: measure results. They post, they connect, they engage, and occasionally they get a client and feel like it worked. But they are not tracking which types of content generated the most leads, which outreach messages had the highest response rates, which posts drove the most profile views, or which conversations turned into clients. Without that data, you are guessing about what to do more of and what to change.</p>
<p>LinkedIn provides a set of analytics through your profile dashboard that gives you basic performance data on your posts and your profile. You can see how many people viewed each post, how many impressions it received, how many people clicked through to your profile from a post, and how many people viewed your profile in a given week. These numbers are not perfect indicators of business impact, but they are directional. A post that gets 10,000 impressions and 200 profile views is working differently than a post that gets 300 impressions and 50 profile views. Both might matter, but for different reasons.</p>
<p>Track your profile views week over week. When you start a new content strategy, make a change to your headline or about section, or run a particularly strong piece of content, notice whether profile views spike. This tells you that your content or profile changes are driving curiosity and sending people to learn more about you. Profile views are a leading indicator of potential leads, because someone who views your profile was interested enough to look more closely.</p>
<p>Beyond LinkedIn''s built-in analytics, keep a simple log of your own. Track the following: number of posts per week, average engagement rate (likes plus comments divided by impressions), number of new connection requests sent and accepted, number of meaningful conversations started in DMs, and number of discovery calls booked from LinkedIn. Reviewing these numbers monthly gives you a clear picture of whether your activity is translating into actual business development progress.</p>
<p>When you identify content that performs unusually well, study it. What was the topic? What type of content was it (story, insight, how-to, question)? What was the opening line? What time did you post it? When you know why something worked, you can replicate the elements that drove that performance. The best LinkedIn content strategies are iterative: you observe what works, do more of it, observe again, and keep refining.</p>
<p>If a certain type of outreach is getting no responses, change it. If your profile gets visitors but no inquiries, look at whether your call to action is clear enough. If you are getting conversations but they are not turning into calls, examine what is happening in those conversations and what friction point is causing them to drop off. Every component of your LinkedIn strategy is measurable and adjustable. Treating it as a system you optimize rather than a fixed set of behaviors is what produces compounding results over time.</p>
<p>Reviewing your LinkedIn analytics does not need to be complicated. Thirty minutes at the end of each month to look at your numbers, identify the two or three things that worked best, and plan to do more of them in the next month is enough. The goal is not to obsess over every data point. The goal is to be informed enough to make better decisions and to course-correct when something is consistently not working. That feedback loop is the difference between a LinkedIn strategy that improves over time and one that stays stuck at the same level indefinitely.</p>
<h3>Do this now:</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Open your LinkedIn analytics dashboard and write down three key numbers: your profile views this week, the total impressions on your most recent post, and the number of people who clicked through to your profile from a post this month.</li>
  <li>Create a simple monthly LinkedIn tracker in a notes app, spreadsheet, or notebook. Include the following fields: posts published, average engagement rate, new connections sent and accepted, DM conversations started, and discovery calls booked.</li>
  <li>Look at your last 10 posts and identify the one that performed best. Write down three reasons you think it outperformed the others. Plan to use those same elements in your next post.</li>
</ul>',
NULL, 4);

